The following passage describes a runtime weight precision swap mechanism for on-device large language model inference. Read it carefully and continue the explanation. The key insight is that during a precision swap, weights of individual layers are replaced atomically while decoding continues, and the choice of how many layers to swap per decode step controls the latency profile observed by the user. Specifically, swapping more layers results in lower memory consumption (fewer bytes), but also increases both computing time (msec) and GPU utilization. The goal is for this swap mechanism to be robust across model sizes with minimal overhead.

